Very good question 👌 — this is where Ruby fundamentals become strong.

You wrote:

def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
  puts "This #{method_name} is not present"
end

And you’re asking:

Why *args?

Why &block?

What is their use?

Let’s break it down properly.

1️⃣ What Ruby Actually Sends to method_missing

Whenever you call a method that doesn't exist:

user.login("admin", "123") { puts "inside block" }

Ruby internally converts it to:

method_missing(:login, "admin", "123", &block)

So Ruby passes:

Method name (:login)

All arguments

The block (if given)

That’s why the method signature must accept them.

2️⃣ Why *args ?
* = Splat Operator

It collects all arguments into an array.

Example:

def test(*args)
  p args
end

test(1,2,3)
# => [1,2,3]

Now in your case:

user.login("admin", "123")

Internally:

method_missing(:login, "admin", "123")

So:

method_name = :login
args = ["admin", "123"]

If you don’t use *args, Ruby will raise an ArgumentError when extra parameters are passed.

3️⃣ Why &block ?
& converts block into a Proc object

If someone calls:

user.login do
  puts "Hello"
end

Ruby passes the block to method_missing.

If your method signature does NOT accept &block,
Ruby will raise an error if a block was given.

4️⃣ What Happens If You Remove Them?
❌ Without *args
def method_missing(method_name)
end

Now this will break:

user.login("admin")

Error:

ArgumentError: wrong number of arguments
❌ Without &block
def method_missing(method_name, *args)
end

Now this will break:

user.login { puts "hi" }

Ruby expects you to accept the block.

5️⃣ Even If You Don't Use Them…

Even if you don’t use args and block,
you MUST define them to match Ruby's internal call structure.

It keeps your method signature compatible.

6️⃣ Why This Matters in Real World

In Rails, method_missing is heavily used in:

ActiveRecord dynamic finders

Association methods

Delegation

Proxy objects

They often forward the call:

def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
  if target.respond_to?(method_name)
    target.send(method_name, *args, &block)
  else
    super
  end
end

Notice how *args and &block are forwarded.

Without them, delegation breaks.

7️⃣ Summary Table

| Syntax      | Meaning                                       |
| ----------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| `*args`     | Collect all arguments into array              |
| `&block`    | Convert block into Proc object                |
| Why needed? | To match Ruby's dynamic method call structure |


🎯 Simple Mental Model

When Ruby can’t find a method:

It says:

"Okay fine… I’ll call method_missing and give you EVERYTHING the user passed."

So your method must be ready to receive everything.

